'''Alfred Constantine Barry''' (July 15, 1815 &ndash; March 5, 1888) was an American educator, politician, and [[Universalist Church of America|Universalist]] minister from [[Wisconsin]].
Born in [[Walton (village), New York|Walton, New York]], Barry was ordained a Universalist minister in 1836. After pastoring churches in New York and [[Richmond, Virginia]], he moved to [[Racine, Wisconsin]], where he started a temperance magazine. He was supervisor of the public schools in Racine 1849-1853 and in 1855 was appointed [[Superintendent of Public Instruction of Wisconsin]] serving until 1858. During the [[American Civil War]], he served as military chaplain. In 1864, he served in the [[Wisconsin State Assembly]]. He died in [[Lodi, Wisconsin]].<ref>'Badgers Saints and Sinners,' Fred L. Holmes, E. M. Hale and Company, Milwaukee, Wisconsin: 1939, pg. 209-211</ref><ref>[http://www.wisconsinhistory.org/dictionary/index.asp?action=view&term_id=1080&search_term=barry Alfred Constantine Barry, Wisconsin Historical Society]</ref>
